04176nam a22006375i 9780857456786DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20062006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574567867 a10.1515/97808574567862doi  a(DE-B1597)636820  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDX210 .V47 2007 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a323.1191/479047a323.11914790471 aVermeersch, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Romani Movement :bMinority Politics and Ethnic Mobilization in Contemporary Central Europe /cPeter Vermeersch. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEthnopolitics ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tList of Tables -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Identities, Interests, and Ethnic Mobilization -- tChapter 2 The Development of Minority Policies in Central Europe -- tChapter 3 Ethnic Politics from Below -- tChapter 4 The Power of Framing -- tChapter 5 International Responses -- tChapter 6 The Romani Movement in Theoretical Perspective -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe collapse of communism and the process of state building that ensued in the 1990s have highlighted the existence of significant minorities in many European states, particularly in Central Europe. In this context, the growing plight of Europe’s biggest minority, the Roma (Gypsies), has been particularly salient. Traditionally dispersed, possessing few resources and devoid of a common “kin state” to protect their interests, the Roma have often suffered from widespread exclusion and institutionalized discrimination. Politically underrepresented and lacking popular support amongst the wider populations of their host countries, the Roma have consequently become one of Europe’s greatest “losers” in the transition towards democracy. Against this background, the author examines the recent attempts of the Roma in Central Europe and their supporters to form a political movement and to influence domestic and international politics. On the basis of first-hand observation and interviews with activists and politicians in the Czech Republic, Hungary and Slovakia, he analyzes connections between the evolving state policies towards the Roma and the recent history of Romani mobilization. In order to reach a better understanding of the movement’s dynamics at work, the author explores a number of theories commonly applied to the study of social movements and collective action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745678640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857456786423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857456786/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK